  "chunk_index": 27,
  "summary": "Dr. Franklin explains to Hastings that he previously declined a job opportunity in Africa for financial reasons, as he needed to maintain his wife's standard of living. When Hastings questions Franklin's lack of grief regarding his wife's suicide, Franklin reveals that he does not believe she committed suicide, though he expresses a firm refusal to investigate or care about the truth of her death.\n\nFollowing the funeral, Stephen Norton appears preoccupied and distant. He approaches Hastings to discuss a moral dilemma using the metaphor of accidentally reading a private letter or looking through a keyhole. Hastings realizes Norton is referring to something he witnessed through a telescope while on a grassy hill with Hastings and Elizabeth Coleridge. Norton admits he saw something while looking for a woodpecker that he considers \"spying.\" While Norton claims this discovery is not directly related to Mrs. Franklin's death, he suggests it might help explain certain things.\n\nHastings suggests that Norton consult Poirot for advice. Although Norton is initially skeptical of Poirot because he is a foreigner, he eventually agrees to seek his counsel. When Hastings informs Poirot of the situation, Poirot becomes grim and warns that the information Norton witnessed is \"very dangerous.\" Poirot instructs Hastings to arrange a casual, inconspicuous meeting with Norton for that evening and asks who else was present during the incident; Hastings responds that Elizabeth Coleridge was also there.",
